@node "1"


     Let me put it this way: CleverViewer is not a viewer in itself. Pretty
scary, isn't it? Actually, it's more like a universal add-on to improve the
existing viewers, which are already excellent. 
     If you use fastview or viewtek regularly, you'll notice that by viewing a
entire drawer they seem to select the pictures almost randomly. Weird enough:
nobody thought of making their soft view the pictures in ALPHABETICAL ORDER! 
     That can be pretty annoying, you see. If you want to make a slideshow of
100 images using fastview, you'll need to leave fastview to choose the order of
viewing or type a script that forces the order of appearance, which means typing
the 100 names correctly. Which is quite tedious, you'll agree!
     So here comes CleverViewer to the rescue! Basically he'll read an entire
directory, order the files alphabetically, write a small script called CV.temp
and launch fastview (or vt or any other CLI viewer).
     In a slideshow, just rename the pics with numbers: 001, 002, 003, ...
     But it's not limited to slideshows, of course. Imagine you've got a drawer
with pictures of famous cities. They're probably named NY1, NY2,... Tokyo1,
Tokyo2,... etc... If you launch fastview, you'll have 4 pics of NY, then 10 pics
of Tokyo, then 10 more pics of NY,... Well not with CleverViewer. 
     Got the picture? CleverViewer is surely not a revolution, but it can help
in many cases. And it's free, so don't bother me, will ya?


@endnode


@node "2"


     CleverViewer works like this:
     
     - First of all, your viewer and CleverViewer must both be in the directory
you want to "cleverview", with all the pictures. That's veryveryvery important.

     - You run the program: the first thing he does, apart from opening a small
window and a progress bar, is to scan the directory he's in. 

     - The next step is to internally order the files alphabetically. You can
see its progression in the progress bar. 

     - Then he scans your viewer's tooltypes (clever eh?) so you can set your
prefs for viewing the pictures. 

     - Next he writes a small script called CV.temp in the same directory.
Notice that you can execute the script without launching CleverViewer. That can
be useful for a slideshow if you don't want to see CleverViewer's GUI! 

     - Finally, he runs the viewer using the script. 
     
     That's it. It couldn't be easier! 


@endnode


